:{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"{{lang|zh|秦始皇本纪第六}}"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA4A"><span lang="zh" title="Chinese language text" id="mwA4E">秦始皇本纪第六</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" id="mwA4I"/></span></a> ["§6: Basic Annals of the First Emperor of Qin"]. Hosted at <span class="nowrap" about="#mwt129" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"{{lang|zh|维基文库 }}&lt;!--sic-->"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA4M"><span lang="zh" title="Chinese language text" id="mwA4Q">维基文库</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" id="mwA4U"/></span> [Chinese Wikisource], 2012. Accessed 27 Dec 2013. <span class="languageicon" about="#mwt130" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"zh icon","href":"./Template:Zh_icon"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA4Y">(in Chinese)</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_Chinese-language_external_links" about="#mwt130" id="mwA4c"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-loserbaby-29" id="cite_note-loserbaby-29"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-loserbaby_29-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-loserbaby_29-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-loserbaby-29" class="mw-reference-text">Beck, B.J. Mansvelt. "<a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/4528373" id="mwA4g">The First Emperor's Taboo Character and the Three Day Reign of King Xiaowen: Two Moot Points Raised by the Qin Chronicle Unearthed in Shuihudi in 1975</a>". <i id="mwA4k">T‘oung Pao</i> 2nd Series, Vol. 73, No. 1/3 (1987), p. 69.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-30" id="cite_note-30"><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-30" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-30" class="mw-reference-text">That both were forbidden has been the general understanding of historians but Beck cites numerous sources from the era employing the latter character in support of the argument that it was not forbidden until the reign of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Second_Emperor_of_Qin" title="Second Emperor of Qin" id="mwA4o" class="mw-redirect"><i id="mwA4s">Second</i> Emperor</a>.<sup about="#mwt966" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-loserbaby_29-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"loserbaby"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-loserbaby-29"}}'><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_note-loserbaby-29" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;" id="mwA4w"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwA40">[29]</span></a></sup></span></li><li about="#cite_note-31" id="cite_note-31"><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-31" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-31" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./King_Zhuangxiang_of_Qin" title="King Zhuangxiang of Qin" id="mwA44">His father</a>'s name <span class="nowrap" id="mwA48"><span lang="zh" title="Chinese language text" id="mwA5A">子楚</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" id="mwA5E"/></span> also became taboo, prompting references to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./State_of_Chu" title="State of Chu" id="mwA5I" class="mw-redirect">Chu</a> to be replaced by its original name "Jing" (<span lang="zh" title="Chinese language text" id="mwA5M">荆</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" id="mwA5Q"/>).<sup about="#mwt910" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-loserbaby_29-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"loserbaby"}}'><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_note-loserbaby-29" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;" id="mwA5U"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwA5Y">[29]</span></a></sup></span></li><li about="#cite_note-baxsag-32" id="cite_note-baxsag-32"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-baxsag_32-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-baxsag_32-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-baxsag-32" class="mw-reference-text">Baxter, William &amp; al. <i id="mwA5c"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://crlao.ehess.fr/docannexe.php?id=1207" id="mwA5g">Baxter–Sagart Old Chinese Reconstruction</a> <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120425064509/http://crlao.ehess.fr/docannexe.php?id=1207" about="#mwt148" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"webarchive ","href":"./Template:Webarchive"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://web.archive.org/web/20120425064509/http://crlao.ehess.fr/docannexe.php?id=1207"},"date":{"wt":"April 25, 2012"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA5k">Archived</a><span about="#mwt148" id="mwA5o"> April 25, 2012, at the </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine" about="#mwt148" id="mwA5s">Wayback Machine</a><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Webarchive_template_wayback_links" about="#mwt148" id="mwA5w"/></i>. 2011. Accessed 26 Dec 2013.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-33" id="cite_note-33"><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-33" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-33" class="mw-reference-text"><span lang="zh" title="Chinese language text" id="mwA50">《汉典》</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" id="mwA54"/> [<i id="mwA58">Chinese Dictionary</i>]. "<a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.zdic.net/z/1a/sw/6211.htm" id="mwA6A">我</a>". Accessed 26 December 2013. <span class="languageicon" id="mwA6E">(in Chinese)</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_Chinese-language_external_links" id="mwA6I"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-34" id="cite_note-34"><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-34" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-34" class="mw-reference-text">This eventually prompted the development of the current pronoun <span lang="zh" title="Chinese language text" id="mwA6M">我</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" id="mwA6Q"/> (<i id="mwA6U">wǒ</i>, "I") from an earlier word meaning "body",<sup about="#mwt998" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-33" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-33"}}'><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_note-33" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;" id="mwA6Y"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwA6c">[33]</span></a></sup> in the sense of referencing oneself as "this [worthless] body" in conversation.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-35" id="cite_note-35"><a href="./Qin_Shi_Huang#cite_ref-35" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-35" class="mw-reference-text"><span class="nowrap" about="#mwt152" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"{{lang|zh|《漢典》}}"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA6g"><span lang="zh" title="Chinese language text" id="mwA6k">《漢典》</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Chinese-language_text" id="mwA6o"/></span>. "<a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.zdic.net/z/27/js/965B.htm" id="mwA6s"><span class="nowrap" about="#mwt153" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nowrap","href":"./Template:Nowrap"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"{{lang|zh|陛}}"}}